# Coding Standards (template)

**Setup:** copy this template to `.harness/CODING_STANDARDS.md` (the real file is gitignored). The review agent loads the real file into the review prompt as `{{CODING_STANDARDS_BLOCK}}`.

**Audiences (progressive disclosure — read only what your role needs):**
- **Implementer + Reviewer** read the **Core rules** and follow them while writing / refactoring.
- **Reviewer** additionally enforces **Binding by reference** (the full `CONTEXT.md` + ADR set) and runs the **Verification cheatsheet**.

If the implement step is wired to read this file (via `AGENTS.md`), the implementer should read the **Core rules** and consult **only** the ADR(s) / `CONTEXT.md` entries relevant to the files it is touching — **not** the whole ADR set (that's the reviewer's job and would bloat implementer context).

> **Design principle (keeps the file from rotting).** Put only **durable engineering principles** in Core. Do NOT copy architecture/domain facts ("the cache is Redis", "X is a frontend-only state", "endpoint Y is owner-only") here — bind them *by reference* to `CONTEXT.md` + Accepted ADRs. Copied facts must be mirrored on every architectural change and rot one feature later; referenced facts never go stale. Keep the body generic; let `CONTEXT.md` + `docs/adr/` carry everything that changes per feature/phase.

Treat each rule as ground truth: refactor within turn budget, or flag in "Concerns".

---

# Core rules (implementer + reviewer)

## Style — Python (backend/)

- `snake_case` for functions, variables, modules. `PascalCase` for classes / Pydantic models / SQLAlchemy models.
- **Type hints on every public function**, including `async def`. Prefer `X | None` and built-in generics (`list[int]`, `dict[str, X]`). Don't introduce new `Optional[X]` / `typing.List`.
- `from __future__ import annotations` at the top of new modules.
- Use dataclasses / Pydantic models — not raw dicts — for structured data crossing **internal** module boundaries. (Shaping a `dict` at the router edge for an HTTP response body is fine.)
- Names read like the domain glossary (`CONTEXT.md`) — never `do_create`, `handle_op`, `process`.

## Style — TypeScript / React (frontend/)

- Prefer **named exports** over default exports. No `any` — if unavoidable, comment why on the same line.
- Function components only; hooks at top level. Reach for `useCallback` / `useMemo` only for a measurable referential-identity reason.
- File naming: `PascalCase.tsx` for components, `camelCase.ts` for utilities and hooks. Tests live next to source as `<module>.test.ts(x)` — no parallel `__tests__/` tree.
- Keep Tailwind class lists short; if `cn(...)` needs > 6 conditional classes, extract a sub-component.
- Immutable updates only — spread or rebuild; never mutate state or props in place.

## Architecture — durable shape

- **Backend layering:** HTTP (router, framework, error mapping) → domain (pure logic, raises typed domain errors, **never imports a web framework**) → persistence (repositories own the queries; no business decisions inside a repository). A web-framework import inside a domain module is a grep-enforceable review block.
- **Frontend:** page components stay thin; push logic into hooks / `lib`. Go through a module's public interface rather than reaching past it. *Which* module owns *which* contract is defined by the code and `CONTEXT.md`, not enumerated here.
- Introducing new module-level mutable state, or a new external dependency / infrastructure (cache, queue, object store, third-party API) that changes the runtime or deployment shape, needs an ADR.

## Tests

- A good test asserts **external behavior**, not implementation details: assert outputs, persisted state, and error / authorization outcomes — never private internals.
- Every new public function gets at least one test. Test names describe behavior: `'rejects 4xx with a normalized ApiError'` ✅, `'test1'` ❌.
- **Backend:** pytest; fixtures in `tests/conftest.py`. **Frontend:** Vitest + MSW for HTTP — no global `fetch` mocking.
- Run the **full** suite before claiming pass. If the environment is broken, report **BLOCKED** — don't summarise expected results.
- Test-infrastructure details (engines, containers, harness wiring) live in the test setup itself, not here.

## Commits

- Conventional Commits: `feat | fix | refactor | test | docs | chore | perf | ci`. Subject ≤ 72 chars, imperative; scope in parens when meaningful.
- Body explains **why**, not what. When fixing a behavioural bug, name the surprising mechanism in one sentence.
- One logical change per commit; refactors separate from features.
- Reference the issue by its **tracker ID** in the body (use whatever tracker the project runs — e.g. bd: `Refs <bead-id>`; GitHub: `Closes #N`).

## What NOT to do

- No `console.log` / `print()` debugging in committed code — use the project's logger.
- No `as any` / `// @ts-ignore` / `# type: ignore` (or language-equivalent) without a same-line comment explaining why.
- No hardcoded secrets / hostnames / ports — env vars, validated at startup.
- No silent error swallowing. At minimum log + rethrow; better, handle at a known boundary.
- No backwards-compat shims for unreleased code paths — just change the code.
- No mutation of function arguments. No nested ternaries (use `if/else` or extract a helper).
- No new term, state, endpoint, or behavior that contradicts `CONTEXT.md` or an Accepted ADR — see **Binding by reference**.

---

# Reviewer-additional — Binding by reference

> **Implementers:** consult only the ADR(s) / `CONTEXT.md` entries that touch the files you're changing. **Reviewers:** read these in full, every review.

- **`CONTEXT.md`** — the domain glossary. Using a defined term to mean something else, or introducing a new term / state / concept without updating `CONTEXT.md` in the same branch, is a review block.
- **`docs/adr/*.md` with `Status: Accepted`** — each ADR's **Decision** and **Consequences** are binding rules. A superseding ADR wins (an Accepted ADR that says "supersedes NNNN" voids NNNN). Check against the *currently-accepted* set, never a snapshot.
- A change that violates an Accepted ADR — or that should have an ADR (hard-to-reverse, surprising, genuine-trade-off) but ships without one — is a review block.

This single section replaces every "per ADR 000X …" rule you would otherwise duplicate above.

---

## Verification cheatsheet (reviewer)

Before marking COMPLETE, run and cite the exit code of the project's full test + typecheck commands (e.g. `pytest tests/`, `npm test --prefix frontend`, `npm run typecheck --prefix frontend`). Only the full run is a valid "tests pass" claim; a broken environment is **BLOCKED**, not a guess.
